3.  **Integrating into Your Workflow:**
    *   Your TypeScript AI agent, when it needs to access documentation or code examples, would call these TypeScript functions.
    *   The retrieved context (text and/or code) would then be injected into the prompt for your LLM, just like any other RAG system.

**Why this is "Best and Most Efficient":**

*   **Efficiency (Development Time):** You're leveraging a huge amount of pre-built, specialized Python code. Your TypeScript work is focused on client-side communication and integrating the results.
*   **Best (Functionality & Maintainability):** You get all the advanced RAG strategies (contextual embeddings, hybrid search, reranking, agentic code search) without having to implement them yourself. Python is arguably the better language for these backend ML/NLP-heavy tasks. The original author will continue to improve the Python server, and you can benefit from those updates by simply pulling the new Docker image.

**Addressing Potential Challenges with Option 1:**

*   **MCP Client in TypeScript:** If a standard MCP client library for TypeScript is not readily available or easy to adapt, directly calling the FastAPI HTTP endpoints (which you can discover from the Python code) is a perfectly viable alternative. FastAPI makes it easy to expose functionality via standard RESTful APIs.
*   **SSE Handling:** If the server relies heavily on SSE for streaming results (which is good for user experience), you'll need to handle SSE in your TypeScript client (Node.js has `EventSource` polyfills or libraries like `eventsource`). The example above provides a basic structure.

By choosing to use the Python server as a microservice, you focus your TypeScript efforts on what TypeScript does best (application logic, UI/workflow control if applicable) and let Python handle the specialized RAG backend tasks. This is a common and effective pattern in modern software architecture.
